            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">The Shukriyya, who themselves trace their ancestry back to Arabia and Ǧaʿfar b. Abī Ṭālib, are one of the most important tribes in Sudan and the largest tribe in the Buṭāna, a region between the Nile, the Blue Nile, and the Atbara. In the 1980s their number was estimated to be 150,000 – 300,000. At that time their way of life was still nomadic or semi-nomadic.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">During the Turkish rule in the 19th century, some sections of the Shukriyya, particularly the Blue Nile Shukriyya, inclined toward agriculture and sedentary life.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p xml:space="preserve"><rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:BPSVRP3E">Hillelson 1920</rs> is an article on the historical poems and 
               traditions of the Shukriyya. In the 1960s and 1970s Hurreiz published three articles on Shukriyya oral poetry 
               (<rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:IVPHVA6X">Hurreiz 1969</rs>, <rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:HNVYN783">Hurreiz 1974</rs>, 
               <rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:HNVYN783">Hurreiz 1978</rs>).</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve"><rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:6YFNZ4E4">Reichmuth 1983</rs> is still the only monograph on 
               the Arabic spoken by the Šukriyya. It offers a comprehensive description of the variety’s phonology and morphology, 
               plus some background information on the tribe and the position of the dialect within the Arabic varieties of Sudan.</p>
            </div>

